# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aden
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] The **10th Railway Engineer Squadron**, known operationally as **10 RW Squadron**.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] The squadron was first formed during the pre-war expansion of the army in 1939 just before Second World War.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] The squadron was finally disbanded in 2013 following the initial Army 2020 reforms.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] On 3 September 1939, the squadron was formed at GHQ, Longmoor Camp.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] Just a little after forming, the squadron was disbanded.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] In May 1940, the squadron was reformed in the Middle-East known as **10th Railway Construction and Operations Company (10 RW Cons and Op Coy)**.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] By July the squadron was based at RAF El Daba, supporting the RAF squadrons there.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] While based, the squadron was tasked with supporting the RAF squadrons through railway construction and support operations.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] Just a little after this, the squadron was moved to Sudan after being replaced by another company.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] By 1943, the squadron was renamed as **10th Railway Construction Company**.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] In October 1943, following the Invasion of Sicily and eventual movement into mainland Italy, the company was assigned to the 1212th Railway Construction Group.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] Following the end of the war, the company was based in Trieste and later Austria.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] In 1947, the company moved to Egypt and assigned to the 10th Transport Regiment.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] Later, the squadron was assigned to Headquarters Railway Group in the Suez Canal Zone and then later the Middle-East Transport Regiment in 1954.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] By May 1955 the company moved to Longmoor and was assigned to the 16th Railway Training Regiment.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] In June of that year, the company was reduced to a cadre but by September was reformed and renamed as **10 Transportation Squadron**.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] After reforming, the squadron joined the former regiment the 16th.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] Just a few weeks after, the squadron was reorganized as a Port for Far East Land Forces (FARLEF).
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] After reorganizing, the squadron moved to Singapore seems to have become independent after this move.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] During this time, the squadron was administered by the 17th Port Transport Regiment.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] During this time, the squadron maintained an independent troop in Hong Kong.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] By 1960, the squadron was assigned to the Engineer Base Group, Singapore.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] In 1964 the squadron was disbanded and their role taken over by the Royal Logistic Corps.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] In 1964 the squadron was disbanded and concurrently reformed that same year as **10 Field Squadron (Airfields)**.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] The squadron was formed at Invicta Park Barracks in Maidstone under 36 Engineer Regiment.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] Formed with the original intention of supporting the troops based in Aden it was No.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] 5004 RAF Airfield Construction Squadron (Airfield Construction Branch RAF) reformed under the Army control.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] In August the next year, the squadron moved to RAF Khormaksar and assigned directly to British Forces Aden.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] In October that same year, the squadron moved location to RAF Sharjah in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] After moving, the squadron was renamed as **10 (Gulf) Field Squadron**.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] By January 1969 the squadron moved back to Longmoore and assigned to the 37th Engineer Regiment.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] After moving back, the squadron was used as Hawker Siddeley Harrier air support squadron.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] In 1969 the Harrier had just been introduced, it was the newest and very first VTOL operational plane.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] It was found that after an examination, the Harrier worked much better in groups instead of individually.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] This created a need for a Harrier Support Group, this formation was the result of the 1966 Defence White Paper.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] From February to April 1971 the squadron deployed, less one troop deployed to Gibraltar on an emergency tour.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] And in April, still without that troop, deployed to Honduras.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] The troop that had been left behind, "A Troop" deployed to Northern Ireland as part of Operation Banner from October 70—January 71.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] By January 1973 the squadron moved to RAF Laarbruch in Western Germany.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] After moving, the squadron was assigned as one of the RAF Support units.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] By 1982 the squadron moved to Mansergh Barracks in Gutersloh under 38th Engineer Regiment.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] Finally, in December 1992 the squadron became "non-operational" and was disbanded in July 1993.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] On 26 February 2004 following the "Delivering Security in a Changing World" reforms of 2003, the squadron was reformed as **10 Field Squadron (Air Support)**.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] The squadron was based at RAF Leeming and assigned to 39 Engineer Regiment (Air Assault).
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] The squadron later deployed on Operation Telic II from June—November 2003.
[src:aden/10th-field-squadron-united-kingdom] The squadron was disbanded on 22 May 2013 following the initial Army 2020 reforms.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The **Aden Emergency**, also known as the **14 October Revolution** or the **Aden Insurgency**, was an armed rebellion led mainly by the National Liberation Front (NLF) and the Front for the Liberation of Occupied South Yemen (FLOSY) against the British Protectorate and Federation of South Arabia.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] It began on 14 October 1963 when tribes from Radfan attacked British troops and ended with the proclamation of independence of the People's Republic of Southern Yemen.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The British had declared a state of emergency following the throwing of a grenade at a gathering of British officials on 10 December 1963 at RAF Khormaksar.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] A state of emergency was then declared in the British Crown colony of Aden and its hinterland, the Aden Protectorate.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The emergency escalated in 1967, hastening the end of British rule in the territory, which had begun in 1839.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Due to the lack of water supply, the barren and inhospitable island of Perim was found unsuitable for troops.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The Sultan of Lahej, Ahmed bin Abdul Karim, then received the detachment for some time at Aden.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] He proposed to enter into an alliance and to grant Aden as a permanent station, but the offer was declined.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] A treaty was, however, concluded with the Sultan in 1802 by Admiral Home Popham, who was instructed to enter into political and commercial alliances with the Chiefs of the Arabian coast of the Red Sea.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] By the early 1800s, the British were looking for a coaling station where they could fuel their steamships through their journey from the Suez Canal to the British Raj.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The British tried to negotiate with the Mahra Sultanate to buy the island of Socotra, located in the Arabian Sea, but the Sultan of Mahra refused, telling the British naval officer tasked with the mission that the island was "the gift of the Almighty to the Mahris".
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] In 1835, a year after the British had given up on Socotra, they had attempted to purchase the port city of Aden and its inlet from the Sultan of Lahej, Muhsin Bin Fadl, but they failed.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] In 1837, the *Duria Dawla*, an Indian ship flying the Union Jack, crashed near the east coast of Aden and was looted by local tribesmen.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] A year after the incident, in 1838, British officials arrived in Lahej and demanded 12,000 Maria Theresa thalers (MTT) as compensation for the losses.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The sultan, unable to pay that sum of money, was forced to cede Aden to the British for a sum of 8,700 MTT a year.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] On 19 January 1839, the British East India Company landed Royal Marines at Aden to retain full control of Aden and stop attacks by pirates against British shipping to India.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Following the landing in Aden, the British established informal treaties of protection with nine sheikhdoms and sultanates in the surrounding region.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] This was more a precautionary measure to prevent the Imams of Yemen from storming Aden, which was something the sheikhdoms did not want to happen.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] These agreements allowed the British to maintain control, using the existing tribal structures to assert their influence.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Since the region was plagued by frequent tribal conflicts and no single ruler held enough sway to unify the tribes, there was little threat to British dominance.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] This fragmentation not only prevented any strong opposition but also delayed the formation of a broader national identity.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The British, in turn, benefited from a system that was both efficient and inexpensive, spending only around $5,435 a year in subsidies to secure the loyalty of twenty-five sultans.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] By avoiding direct administration and relying on a policy of strategic dependence, the British were able to expand their influence.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] By 1914, they had treaties with nearly every sultan in the region.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] In 1914, following the Anglo-Ottoman Convention of 1913, the British and the Ottomans divided Arabia into two parts: the northwest under Ottoman control and influence, and the southeast under British control and influence.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Although a further agreement, which came to be later known as the Violet Line, was negotiated, the Ottomans planned an invasion of the Aden Protectorate in cooperation with local tribes.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] They had gathered significant strength at Cheikh Saïd.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] On 5 November 1914, during the First World War, the British declared war on the Ottomans, who responded with their declaration a few days later, on 11 November.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Although the Ottomans managed to capture the Sultanate of Lahej and reach the city of Aden, they were later expelled by the British.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Around the same time, the British-sponsored Arab Revolt in the Hejaz broke out, diverting Ottoman attention from Aden and effectively ending their campaign.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The Armistice of Mudros, signed in 1918, officially concluded the war and forced the Ottomans out of Arabia, leading to the establishment of the Kingdom of Yemen.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] During the period between the two World Wars, Aden grew significantly in strategic value to the British.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Positioned near the entrance to the Persian Gulf, it played a crucial role in safeguarding maritime routes through the Suez Canal and was close to the newly discovered oil reserves in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Recognizing its increased importance, Britain formally designated Aden as a Crown Colony in 1937 and implemented a full colonial administrative system.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] This move further diminished the authority of local rulers, as Britain took full control over governance and policy decisions.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The centralization of power in British hands sparked several small-scale uprisings.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] In response, Yemeni leaders, often supported by British forces, resorted to harsh and repressive tactics to suppress dissent and maintain order among the tribes.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] In 1952, Arab nationalism began to sweep across the Arab world, starting in Egypt, accompanied by anti-colonial sentiments.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Nationalist pressures prompted the rulers of the Aden Protectorate states to renew efforts at forming a federation.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] On 11 February 1959, six of these states signed an accord to form the Federation of the Emirates of South Arabia.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Over the next three years, nine additional sheikhdoms joined, and on 18 January 1963, Aden Colony was merged with the federation, creating the new Federation of South Arabia (FSA), although all but four sheikhdoms out of twenty-one had joined the union.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Meanwhile, the Qu'aiti and Kathiri sultanates of Hadhramaut, along with Mahra, and Upper Yafa refused to join either of the federations and became the Protectorate of South Arabia, marking the end of the Aden Protectorate.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] On the other hand, the leaders of the sheikhdoms had little experience with federal rule and had no desire for cooperation.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] In addition to all that, there were differences between the sheikhdoms over who should head the federation's new government.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] In 26 September 1962, a successful coup carried out against the Kingdom of Yemen by the Free Officers Movement in Yemen, supported by Egyptian President Gamal Abdel Nasser—who had led the Egyptian Revolution of 1952 against British rule—resulted in the establishment of the Yemen Arab Republic.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] This coup inspired organizations, such as the local branch of the Movement of Arab Nationalists and the Aden Trade Union Congress, to form the National Liberation Front (NLF) and the Front for the Liberation of Occupied South Yemen (FLOSY), respectively.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Supporters of the NLF were from the countryside of Radfan, Yafa', and Ad-Dali, while the supporters of the FLOSY were mainly the citizens of Aden.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] This is because tribal affiliations played a major role in attracting supporters.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] There were a number of different nationalist groups fighting the British.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Among the main players, the SAL was backed by Saudi Arabia, the FLOSY by Egypt and the Aden Trade Unions.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] All the major groups were based in Yemen, and they regularly combined or broke up with other groups.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] For instance, SAL joined with PSP to become OLOS in 1965, and then broke away in 1966.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The NLF joined with OLOS in January 1966 to form FLOSY, then broke away in December 1966.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Such movement was quite common throughout the war.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The British declared a state of emergency on 10 December 1963, following an NLF grenade attack on the British High Commissioner of Aden, Sir Kennedy Trevaskis, which took place as he arrived at Khormaksar Airport to catch a London-bound flight.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The grenade killed the High Commissioner's adviser and a woman and injured fifty other people.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The NLF and FLOSY began a campaign against British forces in Aden, relying largely on grenade attacks.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] One such attack was carried out against RAF Khormaksar during a children's party, killing a girl and wounding four children.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The guerrilla attacks largely focused on killing off-duty British officers and policemen.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Much of the violence was carried out in Crater, the old Arab quarter of Aden.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] British forces attempted to intercept weapons being smuggled into Crater by the NLF and FLOSY on the Dhala road, but their efforts met with little success.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Despite taking a toll on British forces, the death toll among rebels was far higher, largely due to inter-factional fighting among different rebel groups.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] By 1965, the RAF station RAF Khormaksar was operating nine squadrons, including transport units with helicopters and several Hawker Hunter fighter-bomber aircraft.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The army called in these for attacks on rebel positions in which they would use 60-pound high explosive rockets and their 30 mm ADEN cannon.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] On 19–20 January 1967, the NLF provoked street riots in Aden.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] After the Aden police lost control, British High Commissioner Sir Richard Turnbull deployed British troops to crush the riots.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] As soon as the NLF riots were crushed, pro-FLOSY rioters took to the streets.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Fighting between British forces and pro-guerrilla rioters lasted into February.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] British forces opened fire 40 times, and during that period there were 60 grenade and shooting attacks against British forces, including the destruction of an Aden Airways Douglas DC-3, which was bombed in mid-air, killing all the people on board.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] At one point toward the end of the rebellion in early 1967 the NLF killed at least 35 members of FLOSY in 32 days.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The FLOSY guerrillas first asked the British for protection, and then 80 actually flew to the UK using the British passports they had as citizens of a British Colony.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The emergency was further exacerbated by the Six-Day War in June 1967.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Nasser claimed that the British had helped Israel in the war, and this led to a mutiny by hundreds of soldiers in the South Arabian Federation Army on June 20, which also spread to the Aden Armed Police.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The mutineers killed 22 British soldiers and shot down a helicopter (The pilot had to abandon take off from a ledge near Crater, Aden after being hit in the knee by a bullet.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] The Sioux crashed and burned out, but all three occupants escaped), and as a result, Crater was occupied by rebel forces.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Concerns were heightened regarding the ability to give sufficient security to British families in the midst of the increased violence, resulting in evacuation plans for families being sped up considerably.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Following the mutiny, all British forces were withdrawn from Crater, while Royal Marines of 45 Commando took up sniping positions on the high ground and killed 10 armed Arab fighters.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] However, Crater remained occupied by an estimated 400 Arab fighters.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] NLF and FLOSY fighters then took to the streets and engaged in gun battles, while arson, looting, and murder was also common.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] British forces blocked off the two main entrances to Crater.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] They came under sniper fire from an Ottoman fort on Sira island, but the snipers were silenced by a shell from an armoured car.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Order was restored in July 1967, when the 1st Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders entered Crater under the command of Lt.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Colin Campbell Mitchell and managed to occupy the entire district overnight with no casualties.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] On 30 November 1967, the *Federation of South Arabia* ceased to exist when the People's Republic of Southern Yemen was proclaimed.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] In 1967, Israel defeated Egypt in the Six-Day War, thus obliging Egypt to evacuate its troops from Yemen.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] FLOSY, now without any military support from its Egyptian ally, continued fighting the NLF.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] However, FLOSY's fate was sealed when the NLF managed to persuade the Yemen Federal army to join the fight against FLOSY.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] On 7 November 1967, FLOSY tried to attack a federal army base, but the army defeated FLOSY with the NLF's help, inflicting heavy losses on FLOSY.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] After the defeat, FLOSY's fighting force disbanded, although some cadres and leaders remained outside the country.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Most of the opposing leaders reconciled by 1968, in the aftermath of a final royalist siege of San'a'.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] British military casualties in the period 1963 to 1967 were 90 to 92 killed and 510 wounded.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Local government forces lost 17 killed and 58 wounded.
[src:aden/14th-october-revolution] Casualties among the rebel forces stood at 382 killed and 1,714 wounded.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The **Aden riots** of December 2–4, 1947 targeted the Jewish community in the British Colony of Aden.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] During the civil war phase of the 1948 Palestine war, the riots broke out from a planned three-day Arab general strike in protest of United Nations General Assembly Resolution 181 (II), which created a partition plan for Palestine.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The riots resulted in the deaths of 82 Jews, 33 Arabs, 4 Muslim Indians, and one Somali, as well as wide-scale devastation of the local Jewish community of Aden.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The Aden Protectorate Levies, a military force of local Arab-Muslim recruits dispatched by the British governor Reginald Champion to quell the riots, were responsible for much of the killing.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Aden, under British rule since 1839, had a sizable Jewish community—about 8,550 at the time of the riots—living alongside its Muslim population.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Jews and Muslims coexisted relatively congenially, and instances of violence against Jews were highly irregular.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] In the 1940s, however, radical anti-British and anti-Zionist sentiment increased, fomented by the sectarian conflict in Palestine and supported by the proliferation of radios which could catch broadcasts from Cairo and of Egyptian print media, particularly among the learned.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Visits of Palestinian Arabs to Aden and expressions of anti-Jewish sentiments became common.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Additionally, tens of thousands of Arab tribesmen migrated to Aden from North Yemen and the Protectorates during World War II in search of work as manual laborers.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] These conditions contributed to the deterioration of relations between Muslims and Jews and to increased hostility of Muslims toward the Jews in Aden.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] This was an attempt to resolve the Arab-Jewish conflict by partitioning Mandatory Palestine into "Independent Arab and Jewish States and the Special International Regime for the City of Jerusalem".
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Following the vote by the UN on partition of Mandatory Palestine, wide scale protests took place across the Arab countries and communities, with Aden being no exception.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The riots occurred in December 1947, several days after the United Nations' approval of the partition plan.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] On 2 December, a three-day strike was called to protest the decision.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Demonstrations in the Jewish quarter of Aden led to stone and bottle throwing between Jews and Muslims.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Jewish houses and shops were looted, and military control was declared when the crisis exceeded the capacity of the small police force.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The main military force available was the 1,800-strong Aden Protectorate Levies who were locally recruited soldiers with British and Arab officers.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Assistance was also received from several British warships, which sent landing parties, and the equivalent of two companies of British infantry flown in from the Canal Zone.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Order was not restored until 6 December.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The British government was severely embarrassed by the riots, noting privately that they were urging the Arab states to protect their Jews when they themselves were unable to.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The Levies proved unreliable and worse; some fired indiscriminately and probably contributed to the casualties.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The main violence of the riots occurred in three locations.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] In Aden town (also called Crater), an attempt to impose a curfew was largely unsuccessful.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Jewish schools and houses were looted and set alight.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] In the port towns of Steamer Point and Tawahi, most of the Jews were evacuated but some whose presence was not known to the police were killed.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Several Arabs who were apparently innocent were shot accidentally.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] In the Arab town of Sheikh Othman, which had a large Jewish compound, a military contingent arrived to evacuate the 750 Jews to safety.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] However, several declined to leave and were later found dead.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The official casualty count was 76–82 Jews (6 persons were unidentified) and 38 Arabs killed, and 76 Jews wounded.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] At least 87 Arabs were known to have been wounded but many others failed to report their condition.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The dead included one Indian Medical Officer and one Levy.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] More than 100 Jewish shops were looted and 30 houses burned.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] An official enquiry conducted by Sir Harry Trusted determined that many individual Levies were sympathetic to the rioters and did not act to control them.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Nine Levies were imprisoned for looting.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] At least 448 Arabs were arrested for their involvement in the pogroms.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] By 31 December 1947, 226 had stood trial.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Twelve of them received 2-year sentences, 34 received 18-month sentences, and 128 of them received one year in prison or less.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Some offenders were also fined or caned.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The Aden government established a second enquiry, under magistrate K.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Bochgaard, to consider claims for compensation.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Claims totalling more than one million pounds were submitted, exceeding the total annual income of the colony.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] On the grounds that most of the damage was inflicted by non-residents of Aden, Bochgaard awarded £240,000 with a maximum of £7,500 per claim.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] The Aden government then further reduced the maximum per claim to £300 with some options for interest-free loans, much to the anger of the Aden Jewish community.
[src:aden/1947-anti-jewish-riots-in-aden] Shortly after the riots, Aden's Jewish community almost entirely left, together with most of the Yemeni Jewish community.
[src:aden/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] The **1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games** were held in Perth, Western Australia, from 22 November to 1 December 1962.
[src:aden/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Athletic events were held at Perry Lakes Stadium in the suburb of Floreat and swimming events at Beatty Park in North Perth.
[src:aden/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] It was held after the 1962 Commonwealth Paraplegic Games for wheelchair athletes.
[src:aden/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Most venues other than the specifically constructed Lake Monger Velodrome, Beatty Park, and Perry Lakes Stadium, were existing facilities.
[src:aden/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] 35 teams were represented at the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games.
[src:aden/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] (Teams competing for the first time are shown in **bold**).
[src:aden/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] Note: The medals used at these Games were the first to have a neck chain.
[src:aden/1962-british-empire-and-commonwealth-games] All previous games had their medals in presentation boxes.
[src:aden/1993-yemeni-parliamentary-election] The country continued to use the electoral system of North Yemen, with the 301 members of Parliament elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 2026 Aden had a population estimated at 1,194,160, making it one of the largest cities in Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p01] It is the capital and principal part of Aden Governorate, encompassing eight districts.
[src:aden/aden-p01] During the colonial period, the name *Aden* referred to the area along the north coast of the gulf, encompassing Tawahi, Mualla, Crater, and much of Khor Maksar district.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The western harbour peninsula, known as *Little Aden*, now falls within the Al Buraiqeh district.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The city and surrounding area were under British administration from 1839 until independence in 1967.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Before gaining independence, Aden comprised distinct sectors: Crater, the original port; Ma'alla, the modern port; Tawahi, formerly "Steamer Point"; and Gold Mohur resorts.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Khormaksar, on the isthmus connecting Aden to the mainland, hosts diplomatic missions, Aden University's main offices, and Aden International Airport.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden encloses the eastern side of a vast natural harbour that constitutes the modern port.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Little Aden was developed as the site of the oil refinery and tanker port.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Both were established and operated by British Petroleum until they were turned over to South Yemeni government ownership and control in 1978.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden used to be the capital of South Yemen until its union with North Yemen on 22 May 1990.
[src:aden/aden-p01] It has been the temporary capital of Yemen since the start of the Yemeni civil war, hosting some members of the Cabinet of Yemen mainly in al-Maashiq Palace.
[src:aden/aden-p01] It was also the seat of the secessionist Southern Transitional Council from 2018 to 2026.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden is a home and a place for ships, and in Arabic the word "Aden" means residence, and it is said "Aden Al-Balad", meaning the settlement of the country.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Yaqut al-Hamwi said: "It is a famous city on the coast of the Indian Sea, towards the Yemen, and it is poor, with no water or pasture.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Ibn Khaldun said: "This Aden is one of the most fortified cities in Yemen, and it is on the bank of the Indian Sea.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden is an ancient port and was mentioned by the Greeks under the name (Ancient Greek: Αραβία Εμπόριον, romanised: *Arabia Emporion*), which means an Arabic trade port.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The port's convenient position on the sea route between India and Europe has made Aden desirable to rulers who sought to possess it at various times throughout history.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The same work describes Aden as "a village by the shore", which would well describe the town of Crater while it was still little developed.
[src:aden/aden-p01] There is no mention of fortification at this stage.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden was more an island than a peninsula, as the isthmus (a tombolo) was not then so developed as it is today.
[src:aden/aden-p01] At its beginning, the city was a small peninsula with no significant natural resources, but its location between Egypt and India made it important in the ancient Indian Ocean trade route.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The city was the home of the ancient Kingdom of Awsan from the eighth to seventh centuries BC.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In the second half of the first century BC, the Roman Emperor Augustus Caesar determined to control Arabia Felix and reach the Indian Ocean.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aelius Gallus' Roman expedition to Arabia Felix (26–25 BCE) aimed to capture the Sabaean capital of Marib but failed due to extreme desert conditions, disease, and logistical challenges.
[src:aden/aden-p01] After an unsuccessful week-long siege, the army, weakened by illness and dehydration, withdrew, losing most of its ~10,000 troops to environmental factors and disease" The Himyarites overthrew the Kingdom of Sheba in 275 AD and took control of Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Recent incomplete archaeological studies suggest that the Himyarites were the ones who built the huge water cisterns currently known as the "Cisterns of Aden", which stored approximately 136,382,757 litres of water.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Himyarite Kingdom fell in the first quarter of the sixth century AD.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Yusuf Dhu Nuwas mentioned Bab al-Mandab in one of his writings.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The forces of the Kingdom of Aksum were entering Yemen through it.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Byzantine Emperor Justinian I sent a fleet to fight the Himyarite Jews and support the Kingdom of Aksum and the Christians of Najran.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Byzantine sources indicate that the Sasanian Empire took control of the city in 571 AD.
[src:aden/aden-p01] A local legend in Yemen states that Aden may be as old as human history itself.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Some also believe that Cain and Abel are buried somewhere in the city.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Although the pre-Islamic Himyar civilisation was capable of building large structures, there seems to have been little fortification at this stage.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Fortifications at Mareb and other places in Yemen and the Hadhramaut make it clear that both the Himyar and the Sabean cultures were well capable of it.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Thus, watchtowers, since destroyed, are possible.
[src:aden/aden-p01] However, the Arab historians Ibn al Mujawir and Abu Makhramah attribute the first fortification of Aden to Beni Zuree'a.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Abu Makhramah has also included a detailed biography of Muhammad Azim Sultan Qamarbandi Naqsh in his work, Tarikh ul-Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The aim seems to have been twofold: to keep hostile forces out and to maintain revenue by controlling the movement of goods, thereby preventing smuggling.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In its original form, some of this work was relatively feeble.
[src:aden/aden-p01] With the introduction of Islam to Yemen in the seventh century AD, Aden experienced a period of stagnation that lasted until the ninth century AD.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In the early years of Islam, Aden belonged to the province of Jund (Taiz).
[src:aden/aden-p01] It was controlled by the state of Ziyadid and the Sulayhid.
[src:aden/aden-p01] After the death of Ali bin Muhammad Al-Sulayhi, his son took charge of Zurayids, and Aden continued to pay the annual royalty until Queen Arwa bint Ahmed Al-Sulayhi reduced it.
[src:aden/aden-p01] After the fall of the Sulayhid state, the Banu Zurayi became independent in Aden, taking advantage of the Sulayhids' preoccupation with the Khawlan tribes.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Zurayites continued to rule Aden, Lahj, and Abyan for less than forty years until they fell under the Ayyubids' control of the city.
[src:aden/aden-p01] A major battle took place between Turan Shah bin Ayyub and Yasser bin Bilal al-Muhammadi, Minister of State, and the Zurayiyyah were defeated and al-Muhammadi fled to Taiz.
[src:aden/aden-p01] One of the most important contributors to the defeat of the Zurayids was their ongoing wars with the Bani Mahdi in Tihama and the departure of their army to confront the Ayyubids instead of fortifying themselves in Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] After 1175, rebuilding in a more solid form began, and ever since then Aden has been a popular city attracting sailors and merchants from Egypt, Sindh, Gujarat, East Africa and even China.
[src:aden/aden-p01] According to Muqaddasi, Persians formed the majority of Aden's population in the 10th century.
[src:aden/aden-p01] During the Ayyubid period in Yemen, Sanaa and its environs were more hostile to their presence than other regions.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Zaidi tribes were able to defeat the Ayyubids in 1226, but Omar bin Rasul, the founder of the Rasulid state, was able to repel them, so he tightened his control over Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The city regained its position during the days of the Rasulids, so they dug wells and built schools, and Aden flourished commercially.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The kings of Bani Rasul were also merchants and enacted a number of laws and regulations to codify trade in the city.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Banu Tahir were able to control Aden after the Banu Rasool, and the Italian traveller Lodovico di Verthama describes it as one of the most powerful cities seen on Earth during the days of the Tahirids.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1513, the Portuguese, led by Afonso de Albuquerque, launched an unsuccessful four-day naval siege of Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Mamluks in Egypt sensed the danger and sent a force led by Hussein al-Kurdi.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The victorious King Amer bin Abdul Wahhab provided great aid to the Kurds, but he suffered a heavy defeat in the Battle of Diu.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Mamluks sent a second fleet, but the victorious king refused to cooperate with the Mamluks because he had succeeded in repelling the Portuguese from Aden without their help.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Hussein al-Kurdi became angry and allied with the Zaidi Imam, who was opposed to the Tahirids, al-Mutawakkil Sharaf al-Din, and the Tahirid cities fell successively, with the exception of Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Ottoman Empire took control of the city in 1538.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Ottomans' goal was to prevent the Portuguese from controlling Aden, so the city witnessed difficult days, in addition to the fact that the port of Mocha gained greater importance at the expense of Aden during the sixteenth century.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The city's population declined and it turned into a small village with a population of no more than 600 people.
[src:aden/aden-p01] While its population was approximately eighty thousand people during the days of the Rasulid state.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1421, China's Ming dynasty Yongle Emperor ordered principal envoy grand eunuch Li Xing and grand eunuch Zhou Man of Zheng He's fleet to convey an imperial edict with hats and robes to bestow on the king of Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The envoys boarded three treasure ships and set sail from Sumatra to the port of Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] This event was recorded in the book *Yingyai Shenglan* by Ma Huan who accompanied the imperial envoy.
[src:aden/aden-p01] After Ottoman rule, Aden was ruled by the Sultanate of Lahej, under suzerainty of the Zaidi imams of Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The first political intercourse between Lahej and the British took place in 1799, when a naval force was sent from Great Britain, with a detachment of troops from India, to occupy the island of Perim and prevent all communication of the French in Egypt with the Indian Ocean, by way of the Red Sea.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The island of Perim was found unsuitable for troops, and the Sultan of Lahej, Ahmed bin Abdul Karim, received the detachment for some time at Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] A Treaty was, however, concluded with the Sultan in 1802 by Admiral Sir Home Popham, who was instructed to enter into political and commercial alliances with the chief rulers on the Arabian coast of the Red Sea.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The imams relied on the revenues from the port of Mocha, and Aden was not as important as the Abadlahs were.
[src:aden/aden-p01] At the end of the eighteenth century, Sultan *Fadl al-Abdali* concluded an alliance with the Yafi tribes to rebel against the Zaidi imams and monopolise Aden's revenues equally among them.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Sultan of Lahej got rid of the imams, but he did not fulfil his promise to Yafa.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Zaidi imams did not recognise inheritance and saw fighting for the imamate, so the war between *Al-Nasir Muhammad bin Ishaq* and *Al-Mansur Al-Hussein bin Al-Mutawakkil* prolonged, so Al-Abdali took the opportunity to declare his independence in Lahej and Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The English had been visiting Aden and Mocha from 1609, led by Sir Henry Middleton, who was imprisoned, his ships confiscated, and eight of his men killed.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The British tried to conclude treaties with the Zaidi imams after the Ottomans were expelled from Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] They visited Sanaa and Mocha, but they treated the British ambassador poorly and rejected his offer.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Things were different when the Abdali gained independence from Lahj and Medina.
[src:aden/aden-p01] They signed a treaty with the British in 1802, stipulating that they build a factory in Crater and allocate a special cemetery for British subjects free of charge.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Abdali wanted protection from the tribes.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Sultan Fadl bin Ali was killed by Yafi' gunmen, then one of the sheikhs of Al-Hujariya invaded Lahj and besieged it for five months.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Al-Awaliq also besieged it with eight thousand fighters, and they did not leave until Sultan Ahmed bin Abdul Karim paid them seven thousand dollars.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Then the Fadl family attacked Aden in 1836.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1609 *The Ascension* was the first English ship to visit Aden, before sailing on to Mocha during the fourth voyage of the East India Company.
[src:aden/aden-p01] British interests in Aden began in 1796 with Napoleon's invasion of Egypt, after which a British fleet docked at Aden for several months at the invitation of the sultan.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The French were defeated in Egypt in 1801, and their privateers were tracked down over the subsequent decade.
[src:aden/aden-p01] By 1800, Aden was a small village with a population of 600 Arabs, Somalis, Jews, and Indians—housed for the most part in huts of reed matting erected among ruins recalling a vanished era of wealth and prosperity.
[src:aden/aden-p01] As there was little British trade in the Red Sea, most British politicians until the 1830s had no further interest in the area beyond the suppression of piracy.
[src:aden/aden-p01] However, a small number of government officials and the East India Company officials thought that a British base in the area was necessary to prevent another French advance through Egypt or Russian expansion through Persia.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The emergence of Muhammad Ali of Egypt as a strong local ruler only increased their concerns.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The governor of Bombay from 1834 to 1838, Sir Robert Grant, was one of those who believed that India could only be protected by preemptively seizing "places of strength" to protect the Indian Ocean.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Red Sea increased in importance after the steamship *Hugh Lindsay* sailed from Bombay to the Suez isthmus in 1830, stopping at Aden with the sultan's consent to resupply with coal.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Although cargo was still carried around the Cape of Good Hope in sailing ships, a steam route to the Suez could provide a much quicker option for transporting officials and important communications.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Grant felt that armed ships steaming regularly between Bombay and Suez would help secure British interests in the region and did all he could to progress his vision.
[src:aden/aden-p01] After lengthy negotiations due to the costs of investing in the new technology, the government agreed to pay half the costs for six voyages per year and the East India Company board approved the purchase of two new steamers in 1837.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Grant immediately announced that monthly voyages to Suez would take place, despite the fact that no secure coal supplying station had been found.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The British first stationed a coal depot on the island of Socotra in 1834.
[src:aden/aden-p01] However, due to the lack of suitable infrastructure there, they quickly lost interest in Socotra and turned towards Aden instead.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1838, under Muhsin bin Fadl, Lahej ceded 194 km2 (75 sq mi) including Aden to the British.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On 19 January 1839, the British East India Company landed Royal Marines at Aden to definitively conquer the territory (the so-called Aden Expedition) and stop attacks by pirates against British shipping to India.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1850 it was declared a free trade port, with the liquor, salt, arms, and opium trades developing duties as it won all the coffee trade from Mokha.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The port lies about equidistant from the Suez Canal, Bombay, and Zanzibar, which were all important British possessions.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden had been an entrepôt and a way-station for ships in the ancient world.
[src:aden/aden-p01] There, supplies, particularly water, were replenished, so, in the mid-19th century, it became necessary to replenish coal and boiler water.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Thus Aden acquired a coaling station at Steamer Point and Aden was to remain under British control until November 1967.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Until 1937, Aden was governed as part of British India and was known as the Aden Settlement.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Its original territory was enlarged in 1857 by the 13 km2 (5.0 sq mi) island of Perim, in 1868 by the 73 km2 (28 sq mi) Khuriya Muriya Islands, and in 1915 by the 108 km2 (42 sq mi) island of Kamaran.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The settlement would become Aden Province in 1935.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1937, the settlement was detached from India and became the Colony of Aden, a British Crown colony.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The change in government was a step towards the change in the official currency unit.
[src:aden/aden-p01] When British India became independent in 1947, Indian rupees (divided into annas) were replaced in Aden by East African shillings.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The hinterland of Aden and Hadhramaut were also loosely tied to Britain as the Aden Protectorate, which was overseen from Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden's location also made it a useful *entrepôt* for mail passing between places around the Indian Ocean and Europe.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Thus, a ship passing from Suez to Bombay could leave mail for Mombasa at Aden for collection (See *Postage stamps and postal history of Aden*).
[src:aden/aden-p01] In December 1947, a three-day riot broke out in reaction to the drafting of the Partition Plan for Palestine.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The riots and their repression by the Aden Protectorate Levies saw the killing of 76–82 Jews, 33 Arabs, 4 Muslim Indians and 1 Somali, in addition to looting and damaging of property.
[src:aden/aden-p01] After the Suez Crisis in 1956, the British held on to Aden as an outpost in the region for another decade.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The British authorities had already decided to further expand its port shortly before the Suez Canal's 1956 closure.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden sent a team of two to the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games in Perth, Western Australia.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In order to stabilise Aden and the surrounding Aden Protectorate from the designs of the Egyptian backed republicans of North Yemen, the British attempted gradually to unite the disparate states of the region in preparation for eventual independence.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On 18 January 1963, the Colony of Aden was incorporated into the Federation of Arab Emirates of the South against the wishes of North Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The city became the State of Aden and the Federation was renamed the Federation of South Arabia (FSA).
[src:aden/aden-p01] An insurgency against British administration known as the Aden Emergency began with a grenade attack by the communist National Liberation Front (NLF), against the British High Commissioner on 10 December 1963, killing one person and injuring fifty, and a "state of emergency" was declared.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1964, Britain announced its intention to grant independence to the FSA in 1968, but that British troops would remain in Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The security situation deteriorated as NLF and FLOSY (Front for the Liberation of Occupied South Yemen) vied for the upper hand.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In January 1967, there were mass riots between the NLF and their rival FLOSY supporters in the old Arab quarter of Aden town.
[src:aden/aden-p01] This conflict continued until mid February, despite the intervention of British troops.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On 20 June 1967, 23 British Army soldiers were ambushed and shot dead by members of Aden Police during the Aden Mutiny in the Crater District.
[src:aden/aden-p01] During the period there were as many attacks on the British troops by both sides as against each other, culminating in the destruction of an Aden Airways DC3 plane in the air with no survivors.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The increased violence was a determining factor in the British ensuring all families were evacuated more quickly than initially intended, as recorded in *From Barren Rocks to Living Stones*.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On 30 November 1967, British troops were evacuated, leaving Aden and the rest of the FSA under NLF control.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Royal Marines, who had been the first British troops to arrive in Aden in 1839, were almost the last to leave, followed only by the 10 Airfields Squadron of the Royal Engineers, which left Aden on 13 December 1967.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Helicopters of aircraft carrier HMS *Albion* (R07), part of a Royal Navy task force, lifted off the Royal Marine commandos who had been left to secure the airfield.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Qahtan al-Sha'bi assumed the presidency of the new state, and the sheikhdoms of the Eastern Protectorate of Hadramaut and Al-Mahra were annexed to the new state.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Al-Shaabi took over a new country with a collapsed economy.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Civilian workers and businessmen left, and British support ceased.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The closure of the Suez Canal in 1967 played an important role in the country's economy, as it reduced the number of ships crossing Aden by 75%.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The new state was divided into six governorates on 11 December 1967, in order to end the manifestations of tribalism in the state and ignore the tribal borders between the defunct sheikhdoms.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On March 20, 1968, Qahtan dismissed all leftist leaders from the government and party membership.
[src:aden/aden-p01] He was able to put down a rebellion led by leftist factions in the army in May of the same year, and faced new rebellions from leftist parties in July, August and December 1968.
[src:aden/aden-p01] This is because all Arab countries welcomed the front.
[src:aden/aden-p01] National Liberation received a cold reception.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Regimes like Egypt wanted to merge the National Front with the Front for the Liberation of Occupied South Yemen, where the leftist section was more numerous than the supporters of the popular Qahtan.
[src:aden/aden-p01] They wanted a regime that would lead the masses and face the great challenges facing the new state, the most important of which was the bankruptcy of the treasury.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Qahtan al-Shaabi dismissed Interior Minister Muhammad Ali Haitham on 16 June 1969, but the latter, with his ties to the tribes and the army, reassembled the leftist forces that had been dispersed by President Qahtan al-Shaabi, and they were able to place him under house arrest on 22 June.
[src:aden/aden-p01] A presidential committee was formed from Five people: Salem Rabie Ali, who became president, Muhammad Saleh Al-Awlaki, Ali Antar, Abdel Fattah Ismail, and Muhammad Ali Haitham, who became prime minister.
[src:aden/aden-p01] This group took an extreme leftist line, declaring its support for the Palestinians and the Dhofar Revolution, and strengthening its relationship with the Soviet Union.
[src:aden/aden-p01] West Germany severed its relationship with the state due to its recognition of East Germany, and the United States also severed its relationship in October 1969.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The new powers issued a new constitution, nationalised foreign banks and insurance companies, and changed the name of the country to the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen in line with the Marxist–Leninist approach they followed.
[src:aden/aden-p01] A centrally planned economy was established.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The port of Aden was the largest source of national income for the Republic of South Yemen, but the closure of the Suez Canal by Egypt between 1967 and 1975 – reduced commercial activities in the port.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Salem Rubaya Ali wanted to adopt a practical approach, so he communicated with the President of North Yemen, Ibrahim al-Hamdi, and made attempts to restore normal relations with Western countries.
[src:aden/aden-p01] During his presidency, relations between South Yemen and Saudi Arabia were established in 1976.
[src:aden/aden-p01] President Salmin, as he is known, coveted more Soviet support, so the contract with Saudi Arabia worried him.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Soviets pushed them to increase aid, but relations with Saudi Arabia became strained again in 1977 following the assassination of North Yemeni President Ibrahim al-Hamdi.
[src:aden/aden-p01] It is believed that Salem Rabie Ali orchestrated the assassination of Ahmed Hussein al-Ghashmi in revenge for Ibrahim al-Hamdi.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Salem Rabie Ali was subjected to a quick trial that ended with his execution and Abdel Fattah Ismail assuming the presidency of South Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Relations with North Yemen became tense, due to Fattah's support for the factions opposing Ali Abdullah Saleh, who was more fanatical than his predecessors.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Relations with the Soviet Union became active in an unprecedented way, so the Front War broke out in 1978, in which the Soviet Union and the United States intervened.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Ali Nasser Muhammad was able to force Abd al-Fattah Ismail al-Jawfi to resign for "health reasons", and Ismail was exiled to Moscow two years after he assumed the presidency.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Despite the approach of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen and its removal of tribal aspects, tribalism remained alive among politicians and the public despite the exposure of its sheikhs.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Tribal and regional favouritism and nepotism remained rife in southern Yemen, as political forces called on their tribal and regional affiliations during crises.
[src:aden/aden-p01] By January 1986, Aden was torn apart by the rivalry of two factions in the ruling Socialist Party, when President Ali Nasser Muhammad's guards launched a surprise attack on the political party's office in Aden on 13 January 1986.
[src:aden/aden-p01] This was the beginning of the 1986 civil war in South Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Ali Nasser Muhammad was from Abyan Governorate, while most of those killed in the political party office were from Al-Dhalea and Lahj.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Military brigades from those areas bombed Aden from land and sea, forcing Ali Nasser Muhammad to flee and hundreds of thousands of civilians and soldiers to flee to northern Yemen, including Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi.
[src:aden/aden-p01] This was followed by systematic killings and liquidations against the people of Abyan Governorate, on charges that they were collaborating with Ali Nasser Muhammad.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Nearly ten thousand people were killed, and thousands migrated towards North Yemen, most of whom were from Abyan and Shabwa.
[src:aden/aden-p01] With the unification of north and south Yemen in 1990, Aden was no longer a national capital but remained the capital of *Aden Governorate* which covered an area similar to that of the Aden Colony.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On 29 December 1992, Al Qaeda conducted its first known terrorist attack in Aden, bombing the Gold Mohur Hotel, where US servicemen were known to have been staying en route to Somalia for Operation Restore Hope.
[src:aden/aden-p01] A Yemeni and an Austrian tourist died in the attack.
[src:aden/aden-p01] That war marked the end of the state of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen, and Haider Abu Bakr Al-Attas assumed the presidency until May 22, 1990, the unity of South Yemen with North Yemen, and the establishment of the Republic of Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p01] At that time, Ali Salem al-Beidh was considered Ali Abdullah Saleh's deputy, and Haider Abu Bakr Al-Attas was considered prime minister, and after the 1993 elections.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Conflicts began within the ruling coalition, and Vice President Ali Salem Al-Beidh retreated to Aden in August 1993.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The general security situation in the country deteriorated, and the complete integration of the two armies failed.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The southern forces, which were transferred to Amran, clashed with the northern forces there, and the forces of the northern giants, which were transferred to Amran, clashed.
[src:aden/aden-p01] At the forefront of these emerged a group of the brightest officers, such as Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi, who became Minister of Defense at the time; the former Chief of Staff, Major General Abdullah Aliwa; and Major General Salem Qatan, who was assassinated by an Al-Qaeda gunman.
[src:aden/aden-p01] After the war, Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi was appointed Vice President of the Republic, and remained in office.
[src:aden/aden-p01] He held his position until 2012, when he was elected president of the country.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Members of al Qaeda attempted to bomb the US guided-missile destroyer *The Sullivans* at the port of Aden as part of the 2000 millennium attack plots.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The boat that had the explosives in it sank, forcing the planned attack to be aborted.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The bombing attack on destroyer USS *Cole* took place in Aden on 12 October 2000.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 2007 growing dissatisfaction with unification led to the formation of the secessionist South Yemen Movement.
[src:aden/aden-p01] According to *The New York Times*, the Movement's mainly underground leadership includes socialists, Islamists and individuals desiring a return to the perceived benefits of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden remained in a state of political stagnation for 25 years until President Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi took refuge there and carried out his work from the Republican Palace in Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On 7 March 2015, Hadi declared Aden the temporary capital, instead of Sanaa, which he described as occupied by the Houthis.
[src:aden/aden-p01] This was after the Houthis took control of Sanaa on 21 September 2014, and imposed a siege on the Republican Palace and the home of President Hadi on 20 January.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On 22 January, Hadi submitted his resignation to Parliament; it did not hold a session to accept or reject the resignation, and Hadi remained under house arrest imposed by the Houthis.
[src:aden/aden-p01] President Abd Rabbuh Mansur Hadi fled to Aden, his hometown, in February 2015 after being deposed in the coup d'état that many consider to be the start of the Yemeni civil war.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Others consider that the civil war began in September 2014 when Houthi forces took over the capital city Sanaa, which was followed by a rapid Houthi takeover of the government.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Hadi declared in Aden that he was still Yemen's legitimate president and called on state institutions and loyal officials to relocate to Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In a televised speech on 21 March 2015, he declared Aden to be Yemen's "economic and temporary capital" while Sanaa is controlled by the Houthis.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden was hit by violence in the aftermath of the coup d'état, with forces loyal to Hadi clashing with those loyal to former president Ali Abdullah Saleh in a battle for Aden International Airport on 19 March 2015.
[src:aden/aden-p01] After the airport battle, the entire city became a battleground for the Battle of Aden, which left large parts of the city in ruins and has killed at least 198 people since 25 March 2015.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Some Arab and foreign embassies were transferred to Aden, and Defense Minister Mahmoud Al-Subaihi was able to leave Sanaa for Aden and met with President Hadi.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On March 4, 2016, unidentified gunmen stormed the Mother Teresa House in the city and killed sixteen people, including four nuns.
[src:aden/aden-p01] A number of the old city's churches have also been destroyed by Islamic extremists since mid-2015.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On 14 July 2015, the Saudi Arabian Army launched an offensive to win control of the city.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Within three days, the city was cleared of Houthi rebels, ending the Battle of Aden with a coalition victory.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Beginning on 28 January 2018, separatists loyal to the Southern Transitional Council (STC) seized control of the Yemeni government headquarters in Aden in a coup d'état against the Hadi-led government.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Prime Minister Maeen Abdulmalik Saeed, his ministers and his entourage were conducted to safety under the barrage of hostile fire.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On 7 January 2026, the Yemeni government forces managed to control Aden following the collapse of the Southern Transitional Council.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The entry of the Yemenis into Islam contributed to their abandoning their ancient script and replacing it with the late Nabataean alphabet in which the Qur'an was written.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Today, Yemenis speak Arabic in the Yemeni dialect, which is a developed dialect and closely linked to the ancient language.
[src:aden/aden-p01] It has three dialects with branches: the Sanʽani dialect, the Hadrami dialect, and the Taʽizzi-Adeni dialect, in addition to the Bedouin dialect of the residents of Marib.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Al Jawf, Shabwa, and Inner Hadhramaut, and each of these dialects has characteristics and features.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Adeni art or the *Adeniyat* is an art of Arabic music.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Among the ancient artists of Aden are Iskander Thabet Saleh and Muhammad Murshid Naji, and among the poets are Abdul Rahman Ibrahim Muhammad, Ahmed Ghaleb Muhammad Al-Jabri, Abdullah Abdul Karim Muhammad, Ali Abdullah Jaafar Aman, Farid Muhammad Barakat, Lotfi Jaafar Aman, and Mohsen Ali Brik.
[src:aden/aden-p01] "Adeni music" played a major role in Aden society, and artists in the Aden dialect were called "al-Mutariba", meaning people of music.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Adeni music began in 1920 when the army of the Aden Protectorate was formed, and after it the National Guard, where there were teams for those forces and those teams participated On special occasions and weddings.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The city of Aden is considered the first city in which sports were practiced in the Arabian Peninsula, and the first private club in Aden was founded in 1905 under the name "Al-Ittihad Al-Muhammadi Club", as the first sports club in Yemen and the Arab world.
[src:aden/aden-p01] He was fighting the occupation army divisions and the fleet divisions coming and passing to the port of Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1924, the "Al-Husseini Sports Club" was founded in Crater, and a third club appeared in Tawahi under the name "Al-Bamboot Club" and Sheikh Othman.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The 1930s witnessed the emergence of a number of clubs.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1933, the "Nujoom Al-Layl Club", Al-Aidrousi Club, and Nujoom Al-Sabah Club appeared in Crater, and in Tawahi, the "Al-Ittihad Al-Islami Club" (Al-Mawlada) appeared.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Until that year, football matches were played in a friendly manner between the teams of the Crater, Al-Tawahi, and Sheikh Othman regions, as there were no federations regulating sports activity.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1934, the occupation authority announced the establishment of a sports association called the "Adeniya Sports Association", after the increasing number of local clubs.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Its members were appointed by the Governor-General of Aden, and all of its members were English, headed by the English Governor of Aden, Bernard Reilly, as sponsor.
[src:aden/aden-p01] The association's board of directors consists of Hikam Bottom as president, the Indian Rosario as secretary, and two other members.
[src:aden/aden-p01] This association began holding the first club tournament, which was the "Rosario Cup Championship".
[src:aden/aden-p01] Among the most important tournaments held in Aden before independence were the Rosario Cup, the Riley Cup, the Somali Bassem Al-Nar Cup, the Aramco Cup, and the Kik Muncherji Championship.
[src:aden/aden-p01] After independence, the "Football Federation" was established on January 18, 1968, on the ruins of the "Adeniya Sports Association".
[src:aden/aden-p01] The Federation took a decision regarding the Adeniya clubs, which had numbered about 64 sports clubs, reducing and merging the clubs in Aden and Lahj to only 16 clubs, and the clubs were forced to join or unite with large teams.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In February 1968, several sports clubs were abolished, leaving only 12 clubs remaining.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In December 1968, Al-Islah Club and Al-Shaab Club were merged into one club under the name of the latter in Al-Tawahi.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In 1969, the Al-Ittihad Al-Muhammadi Club and Al-Tadamon Club were united in Crater, under the name Al-Tadamon Al-Muhammadi Club.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In the "First General Sports Conference" in 1973, the clubs were merged and reduced again, so that their number became only 7 clubs: Al-Ahrar Club, Al-Ahly Club, Shamsan Club, Al-Shaab Club, Al-Hilal Club, United Youth Club, and Aden Tennis Club.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On July 18, 1975, the stage of forming urban clubs, and the beginning of the stage of politicisation of the clubs in favour of the National Liberation Front, took place.
[src:aden/aden-p01] It was decided to change their names and reduce them to become 5 clubs: Al-Tilal Club, Shamsan Club, Al-Minaa Club, Al-Wahda Club, and Al-Shoula Club.
[src:aden/aden-p01] On July 18, 1975, the "Al-Tilal Sports Club" appeared, headed by Yassin Saeed Noman, as a new name for the "Al-Ittihad Al-Muhammadi Club", which was founded in 1905, and in 1976 the "Yemeni Football Federation" appeared.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Football is the most popular sport in Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p01] There are 9 stadiums in Aden, including the May 22 International Stadium, and 10 sports clubs.
[src:aden/aden-p01] In November 2010, Aden hosted the 2010 Arabian Gulf Football Cup.
[src:aden/aden-p01] Aden has several historical and natural sites of interest to visitors.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The industrial activity in Aden is represented by a group of factories and production units, the forefront of which is the oil refinery.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The oil refinery in Aden is considered one of the first refineries to be established in the region, and began operating in 1954 AD.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The Aden Refineries Company has facilities such as an oil tanker port, a network of storage tanks, and a centre to supply ships with fuel.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Historically, Aden was a station for importing goods from the African coast and from Europe, the United States, and India.
[src:aden/aden-p02] As of 1920, Aden was a major commercial centre for trade in the Arabian Peninsula, and the port exported small quantities of local products to most Arab ports.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Aden provided coal and salt to passing ships, and the port was a stopping point for ships when they entered Bab al-Mandab.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Historically, the port of Aden was the main transport port in the region.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Passenger ships land in Al-Tawahi District, and the city is served by Aden International Airport, which is about 10 kilometres (6 mi) from the city.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The airport is the main headquarters of Al-Saeeda Airlines and its operations centre.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The airport is considered the second largest airport.
[src:aden/aden-p02] In Yemen, after Sanaa International Airport, it is considered the best airport in Yemen in terms of location due to the mountainous nature of Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p02] However, this airport is surrounded by the Arabian Sea in terms of take-off and landing.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The establishment of Aden Airport dates back to the year 1927 when the British forces established a military airport in the district.
[src:aden/aden-p02] After World War II, Britain carried out extensive urban modernisation and built Aden International Airport, known today, next to the military airport.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Alyemda Airlines was the official carrier of South Yemen, before unification, and was based in Aden, before merging with Yemen Airways in 1996.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Before the Battle of Aden Airport and the 2015 military intervention in Yemen closed this airport along with other airports in Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p02] On 22 July, Aden International Airport was declared fit for operation again after the Houthi forces were driven from the city, and a Saudi plane carrying aid reportedly became the first plane to land in Aden in four months.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The same day, a ship chartered by the World Food Programme carrying fuel docked in Aden's port.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Historically, Aden's harbour has been a major hub of transportation for the region.
[src:aden/aden-p02] As of 1920, the harbour was 13 by 6 km (8 by 4 mi) in size.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Passenger ships landed at Steamer Point now called Tawahi.
[src:aden/aden-p02] During the British colonial period motor vehicles drove on the left, as in the United Kingdom.
[src:aden/aden-p02] On 2 January 1977, Aden, along with the rest of South Yemen, changed to driving on the right, bringing it into line with neighbouring Arab states.
[src:aden/aden-p02] During the early 20th century, Aden was a prominent export centre for coffee grown in the Jubail highlands.
[src:aden/aden-p02] And also to export frankincense, wheat, barley, alfalfa and millet, which are produced and exported from Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The leaves and stems of clover, millet, and corn produced in Aden were generally used as fodder.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Beginning in 1920, Aden was desalinating seawater to produce table salt.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Between 1916 and 1917, Aden produced more than 120,000 tons of salt.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Aden also produced potash, which was exported to Mumbai.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Historically, Aden would import goods from the African coast and from Europe, the United States, and India.
[src:aden/aden-p02] As of 1920, the British described it as "the chief emporium of Arabian trade, receiving the small quantities of native produce, and supplying the modest wants of the interior and of most of the smaller Arabian ports." At the docks, the city provided coal to passing ships.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The only item being produced by the city, as of 1920, was salt.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Also, the port was the stop ships had to take when entering the Bab-el-Mandeb; this was how cities like Mecca had received goods by ship.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Yemen Airlines, the national airline of South Yemen, had its head office in Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p02] On 15 May 1996, Yemen Airlines merged with Yemenia.
[src:aden/aden-p02] During the early 20th century Aden was a notable centre of coffee production.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Women processed coffee beans, grown in the Yemen highlands.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Frankincense, wheat, barley, alfalfa, and millet was also produced and exported from Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The leaves and stalks of the alfalfa, millet and maize produced in Aden were generally used as fodder.
[src:aden/aden-p02] As of 1920, Aden was also gathering salt from salt water.
[src:aden/aden-p02] An Italian company called Agostino Burgarella Ajola and Company gathered and process the salt under the name Aden Salt Works.
[src:aden/aden-p02] There was also a smaller company from India, called Abdullabhoy and Joomabhoy Lalji & Company that owned a salt production firm in Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Between 1916 and 1917, Aden produced over 120,000 tons of salt.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Aden has also produced potash, which was generally exported to Mumbai.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Charcoal was produced as well, from acacia, and mainly in the interior of the region.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Cigarettes were produced by Jewish and Greek populations in Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The tobacco used was imported from Egypt.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Since the outbreak of the Yemeni Civil War spread to Aden in 2015, the city has been struck by constant protests over a range of issues, but especially concerning electricity generation.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Aden's power grid is composed solely of diesel generators and is thus heavily dependent on imported fuel.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The main power plant is al-Hasswa diesel power plant, which in June 2021 had only two turbines out of five running, producing up to 50 megawatts (MW) of power in a region where the deficit hovers around 300 MW.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Nawfal al-Mojamal, the plant director, said "In its 35 years of existence, al-Hasswa station never had any kind of maintenance, except in 2016 ... when the two turbines were restored".
[src:aden/aden-p02] This electricity shortage led to the development of Yemen's first large-scale solar power plant servicing Aden with a 120 MW capacity, opened in July 2024.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The free zone, which was opened in 1991, represents Yemen's economic gateway and the meeting point of the continents of Asia and Africa.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The free zone gains its strategic importance from the special location of the port of Aden, as it is located directly on the main trade route around the world and from the Middle East to Europe and America, and is distinguished by the possibility of providing transit services.
[src:aden/aden-p02] To East Africa, the Red Sea, the Indian subcontinent and the Arabian Gulf.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The free zone represents a storage and distribution area suitable for Africa, the Red Sea and the Arabian Gulf.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Aden is located on the coast of the Gulf of Aden, and is about 363 kilometres from the capital, Sanaa.
[src:aden/aden-p02] It is located between latitudes 47 and 12 north of the equator, and at an altitude of 6 metres above sea level.
[src:aden/aden-p02] It is surrounded by Lahj Governorate to the north and east, and the Governorate of Abyan is to the northwest.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Aden has an airport (Aden International Airport), a seaport (the port of Aden), and has land routes from the north linking it to Hajj, Abyan and Taiz.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Aden is a coastal city; it overlooks the Gulf of Aden, which opens to the Indian Ocean.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The shape of the city of Aden in the form of two peninsulas helped this factor to make the city of Aden unique in this particularity, which clearly affected the occurrence of the phenomenon of land and sea breezes.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Which occurs due to air exchange between land and water during the day and night.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Its location on the water surface also affects the daily and annual temperature range.
[src:aden/aden-p02] This does not mean that there are no significant differences in temperatures in summer and winter.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Aden has a hot desert climate (BWh) in the Köppen-Geiger climate classification system.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Although Aden sees next-to-no precipitation year-round, it is humid throughout the year.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Most of the coasts of Aden Governorate along the coastal strip are sandy coasts, and the governorate has coastal beaches, including the Golden Coast in Al-Tawahi District, the coast of Abyan Bakhour Maksar, Al-Ghadeer Beach, and Kud Al-Nimr Beach in Buraiqa.
[src:aden/aden-p02] There are about 21 islands around the peninsulas of Aden, Aden Lesser, and Ras Amran.
[src:aden/aden-p02] They are mostly rocky islands, some of which are surrounded by incomplete coral reefs, and most of them are considered fishing areas.
[src:aden/aden-p02] A number of islands have many activities, especially on Al-Ummal Island and Sirah Island.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Yemen is considered one of the countries rich in bird species in the Middle East due to the availability of many suitable coastal environments that helped attract many migratory birds to wetland sites, coasts and islands.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The Aden region (Khor Maksar – Al-Haswah) was registered on the list of important areas of the World Bird Organization as a habitat.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The last three species that are globally threatened with extinction are: the great eagle, the gull eagle, and the eastern king eagle.
[src:aden/aden-p02] There are dozens of bird species recorded in the wetlands of Aden and the Caltex swamp area, which are rich in a wide variety of endemic and migratory birds, including birds that are present throughout the year.
[src:aden/aden-p02] There are many birds in the area, including great flamingos, dwarf flamingos, and rock egrets.
[src:aden/aden-p02] And the spoonbill, the hooked tern and the seagull.
[src:aden/aden-p02] There are 95 schools in Aden, including 13 kindergartens, and 82 basic education schools, including 29 schools for boys, 29 schools for girls, and 29 joint schools for boys and girls.
[src:aden/aden-p02] There are also 29 secondary schools, including 15 schools for boys and 14 schools for girls, all of which are in a double shift system.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Until 2004, the number of male students reached In basic education, there were 57,941 students and 48,081 female students, with a total of 104,622 students.
[src:aden/aden-p02] In secondary education, the number of male students reached 11,029 students, and 9,643 female students.
[src:aden/aden-p02] As for vocational, technical and vocational education centres and institutes, their number is 13, with 2,214 students enrolled, including 453 teachers.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The health institutes have one institute, with 864 students enrolled, including 147 teachers, according to 2010 statistics.
[src:aden/aden-p02] As for higher education, there is one government university in Aden, which is the University of Aden, which has 9 colleges.
[src:aden/aden-p02] More than 29 thousand students are enrolled, according to 2010 statistics.
[src:aden/aden-p02] There are 15 hospitals in the economic capital, Aden, including 5 public government hospitals, 6 belonging to the private sector, and 37 health centres.
[src:aden/aden-p02] There are 34 facilities in the city that provide maternity and childhood services, and the number of specialised workforce in health facilities is 2,825 specialists.
[src:aden/aden-p02] In June 2015, the International Red Cross team present in conflict areas in Yemen during the events of the Yemeni civil war announced that the cities of Crater, Al-Mualla, Khor Maksar and Al-Tawahi in the Aden Governorate in the south of the country were areas affected by dengue fever.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The health authorities in Aden said that this fever had spread remarkably and widely.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Since the beginning of May, health services have deteriorated and infrastructure facilities, such as electricity, water, and sanitation, have been damaged as a result of the ongoing fighting in the city for months.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Aden has known mail since June 15, 1839, that is, a year after the British occupation, although the official post office was not inaugurated until 1857.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Postage stamps of both Britain and India were used in Aden until it became called the Aden Colony on April 1, 1937, although the stamps of this stage It bears no distinctive sign, but the use of the number 124 as a postal code is attributed to Aden as part of the Indian postal numerical system.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Then, when it became a colony in 1937, it had sets of postage stamps containing pictures and the name Aden printed on them.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The weekly *Al-Amal* newspaper was founded in 1957 in Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Its slogan was "Freedom, Bread, and Peace".
[src:aden/aden-p02] The British authorities allowed only 1,500 copies to be printed weekly, and the newspaper was banned shortly afterward.
[src:aden/aden-p02] In 1958, *Al-Ayyam*, an independent daily newspaper in the Arabic language, was established in Aden during the British occupation.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The first issue was published on 30 July 1958, and its founder and editor-in-chief was Brigadier General Muhammad Ali Bashraheel.
[src:aden/aden-p02] It stopped publishing after independence during the era of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen, and then resumed publication.
[src:aden/aden-p02] After achieving Yemeni unity, the first issue of the second edition was on 7 November 1990, after a hiatus that lasted more than 23 years.
[src:aden/aden-p02] In 1998, *Al-Ayyam* was the first newspaper in Yemen to be prosecuted by the government under a criminal law.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Other cases followed until it became public by the end of the year.
[src:aden/aden-p02] 2008, responsible for 73% of the total number of cases filed by the Ministry of Information and the Yemeni government against the press in Yemen.
[src:aden/aden-p02] On 12 May 2009, security forces launched an attack on the headquarters of *Al-Ayyam* newspaper in Aden.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Radio Aden was established on 17 August 1954, under the name "Aden Radio Station".
[src:aden/aden-p02] It is currently broadcast in two periods, morning and evening.
[src:aden/aden-p02] The British occupation opened the Aden Channel on 11 September 1964, following the revolution of 14 October 1963.
[src:aden/aden-p02] Television transmission was limited to covering populated neighbourhoods in the city of Aden, especially where soldiers and families of the British forces were present.
[src:aden/aden-p02] In January 1979, the television headquarters moved to the "Radio and Television Building" in Tawahi; at that time broadcasts were in black-and-white.
[src:aden/aden-p02] In March 1981 the gradual transition to colour broadcasting began, and in June 1981 the channel began broadcasting via satellite.
[src:aden/aden-p02] After the Yemeni unification on 22 May 1990, Aden Channel was the second official channel of Yemeni TV.
[src:aden/amran-governorate] 'Amran Governorate is divided into the following 20 districts.
[src:aden/amran] 'Amran has a long history, dating to the pre-Islamic era.
[src:aden/amran] During that period, it was one of the main centers of the Bakil tribal confederation.
[src:aden/amran] At the time of the Sabaean kingdom, the town blossomed into a fortress.
[src:aden/amran] A series of bronze plaques from that time were found in the town in the mid-nineteenth century and are now in the British Museum.
[src:aden/amran] In the seventh century, the town witnessed clashes against the Sabeans.
[src:aden/amran] Remains of carved stones that belonged to former temples and palaces bear witness to past glory.
[src:aden/amran] A large stone inscription is found on the western city gate (Bab al-Kabir).
[src:aden/amran] 'Amran is largely absent from medieval sources, and the nearby fortified town of al-Jannat eclipsed it in importance during this period.
[src:aden/amran] This may have been partly because 'Amran, located in the middle of the al-Bawn plain, was less defensible, whereas al-Jannat had a more strategic location.
[src:aden/amran] The 10th-century writer al-Hamdani described the ancient palace at 'Amran, but he gives no details about its population or any indication that it was still occupied.
[src:aden/amran] From the late 14th century onward, 'Amran appears to have emerged as a strategic site, and it appears frequently in historical texts such as the *Ghayat al-Amani* of Yahya ibn al-Husayn during this period.
[src:aden/amran] Then, in the 1500s and 1600s, 'Amran is mentioned as a more generally important city.
[src:aden/amran] ʿAmran is completely surrounded by walls which date to 1720.
[src:aden/amran] The surrounding landscape is dominated by terraced landscapes with stone walls to counteract erosion of fertile arable land.
[src:aden/amran] The old souq is noted for its stone columns.
[src:aden/amran] The road through the city from Sana'a was modernized following Chinese investment, and is over 200 km (120 mi) long.
[src:aden/amran] The old medical centre has been transformed into a small public hospital.
[src:aden/amran] The city is located in a fertile area in what was the centre of the area's coffee industry.
